I have been given a nonlinear system of ODEs which has arisen out of a colleague's engineering research: $$\begin{array}{rcl}
\dot{x}_0&=&x_1\\
\dot{x}_1&=&-\frac{\lambda}{(x_2)^n-k^2\lambda}x_0\\
\dot{x}_2&=&\frac{2nx_0x_1\lambda(x_2)^n}{2n(x_2)^{2n-1}-2n\lambda k^2(x_2)^{n-1}-n(n-1)(x_0)^2\lambda(x_2)^{n-1}}
\end{array}$$ (I have values for $\lambda$, $k$ and $n$, and also some initial conditions). Basically all I want is an (open source) computer system to fling them at, and see what happens. I have so far tried Octave and its "lsode" command (no good; gave errors), Python with "odeint" from sympy.integrate (gave a solution); I need to test out a few others. I am far from being an expert (or even vaguely competent) at non-linear ODE systems, and I'm hoping for advice as to which system I can use with confidence to generate trustworthy numerical solutions.
